 This problem is about inverse variation, which means that as one quantity increases, the other decreases, and vice versa. We can use the formula for inverse variation, (\text{variable 1})(\text{variable 2}) = \text{constant.} In this case, the handle length is one variable, and the force is the other. So, (\text{force}) = \frac{(\text{constant})}{(\text{handle length})}. </think> <answer> If a 9-inch wrench requires 375 pounds of force, then (\text{force}) = \frac{(\text{constant})}{(\text{9})}. We can solve for the constant:
\begin{align}
375 & = \frac{\text{constant}}{9}\\
3400 & = \text{constant}
\end{align} The constant is 3400. If a 15-inch wrench is used, then (\text{force}) = \frac{3400}{15} = \frac{680}{3}. </answer>

